1. Dataset

The dataset contains intentional homicide rates, suicide rate and gross domestic product (GDP) from 1970 to 2020 by country. The data source is the world bank. I found the dataset on kaggle.

# import dataset
shg_original <- rio::import("data/suicide_homicide_gdp.csv")

Describing the Dataset

There are 13â566 observations with 10 variables. The country name is represeneted in three different ways. Once completely written out (Â«countryÂ»), once abbreviated according to the iso standard with 3 characters (Â«iso3cÂ») and once abbreviated according to the iso standard with 2 characters (Â«iso2cÂ»).

# number of observations
nrow(shg_original)
## [1] 13566
# numer of variables
ncol(shg_original)
## [1] 10

Describing Variables, Type and Measurement Level

The dataset shows observations from 1970 to 2020 (Â«yearÂ») as a integer data type. Further there are four numerical values: Â«Intentional homicides (per 100,000 people)Â», Â«Suicide mortality rate (per 100,000 population)Â», Gross Domestic Product Â«GDP (current USD)Â» and Â«GDP per capita, PPP (current international $)Â». Intentional homicides and suicide mortality rate are discrete values. Gross domestic product (GDP) is a continuous variable, a monetary measure of the market value of all the final goods and services produced and sold (not resold) in a specific time period by countries. Gross domestic product (GDP) per capita is a financial metric that breaks down a countryâs economic output per person and is calculated by dividing the GDP of a nation by its population. The values of the GDP per capita reach from 285.4 to 153563.9.

Finally, the region (Â«adminregionÂ») and income level (Â«incomeLevelÂ») are specified as characters. Region and income level are categorical variables. Income level is somewhat ordinal with the following values: Aggregates, High income, Low income, Lower middle income and Upper middle income. A few variables are not classified, others are aggregates. I will remove them later.

Research Questions

Do intentional homicides correlate with gross domestic product (GDP) in genereal? What are the differences in regions over the years?

Does a high homicide rate favor a high suicide mortality rate?

2. Summary Statistics

Removing Incomplete Observations

Transforming the data for easier handling. Also, the dataset contains lotâs of variables with NA. Removing those NAâs leaves 2352 observations.

# creating a new dataset from the original data
shg <- shg_original

# renaming the variables to easier names
shg <- rename(shg, IntHomicides = `Intentional homicides (per 100,000 people)`,
              SuicideMort = `Suicide mortality rate (per 100,000 population)`,
              GDP = `GDP (current US$)`,
              GDPcap = `GDP per capita, PPP (current international $)`,
              region = `adminregion`)

# removing all observations with NA's
shg <- shg %>% 
  filter(incomeLevel != "Aggregates" & incomeLevel != "Not classified" ) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(IntHomicides)) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(SuicideMort))

3. Data Transformation

Removing More Incomplete Observations

The column Â«iso3cÂ» is not necessary. Further I discovered a few total rows in between the rest of the data, which should be removed.

# create a new subset
shg_trnsf <- shg %>% 
  select(-iso3c) %>% # remove column iso3c
  filter(iso2c != "") # remove rows (total per region)

Merge With Another Dataset

As the regions in the dataset are incomplete and do not match the ISO standard, I imported a proper list (Â«regionÂ») with countries and their regions, then merging the two tables together. I used mergeas I could not figure out how it works with inner_join.

# import a second dataset
region <- rio::import("data/region.csv")

# rename columns for easier merging
region <- rename(region, iso2c = `alpha-2`,
                 regionISO = `region`)

# combining with another dataset
shg_exp <- merge(x = shg_trnsf, y = region, by = "iso2c")

Suicide Mortality Rate by Sub-Regions

This makes more sense to only show one year and compare the sub-regions. So creating a subset, group, summarise and arrange descending.

# create a subset
shg_2018 <- shg_exp %>%
  filter(year == 2018) %>% # only observations from 2018
  group_by(`sub-region`, regionISO) %>% # grouped by sub-region and region (for colour fill)
  summarise(sumSuicideMort = sum(SuicideMort)) %>% # calculate sum
  arrange(desc(sumSuicideMort)) # order descending

# create a subset
shg_2018_top20 <- shg_exp %>%

Function for Regression Table in R Markdown

Creating a function to compile the regression table.

# create wrapper around stargazer
starviewer <- function(...) {
  
  # make sure stargazer is available
  require(stargazer)
  
  # assume text output but check for latex or html
  star_format <- "text"
  if(knitr::is_latex_output()) {star_format <- "latex"}
  if(knitr::is_html_output())  {star_format <- "html"}
  
  # if latex, just run stargazer as usual
  if (star_format == "latex") {
    stargazer::stargazer(...)   

  } else {

  # if not latex, run stargazer in text / html (or both)  
    dir <- tempfile()
    dir.create(dir)
    htmlFile <- file.path(dir, "tempfile.html")
    stargazer::stargazer(..., type = star_format, out = htmlFile)
    rstudioapi::viewer(htmlFile)
  }
}

Regression Table

The p-value should be smaller than 0.05. This is the case for model 2 and model 3. Not for model 1.

R-Squared (RÂ² or the coefficient of determination) is a statistical measure in a regression model that determines the proportion of variance in the dependent variable that can be explained by the independent variable. The R-Squared values are pretty low, they can explain the Suicide Mortality only very little (between 2 and 15 percent). The Adjusted R-squared is always smaller than the R-squared as it is aligned with the number of variables.

A closer look at model 3 (âfit3â): The region has a significant effect on the suicide mortality rate, but not allways in the same directions and not for Ozeania.
